'''Nagamochiyama Kofun''' (長持山古墳) is a round-shaped {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|12=draft}} located in Sawada, [[Fujidera City]], [[Osaka Prefecture]]. The name "Nagamochiyama" derives from the {{ill|house-shaped stone coffin|ja|家形石棺|1=House-shaped Sarcophagus|12=draft}} exposed at the mound's summit. Two stone coffins have been excavated from the site.

== Overview ==
The kofun is situated southwest of the rear circular section of {{ill|Ichinoyama Kofun|ja|市ノ山古墳|12=draft}} (allegedly the burial site of Emperor Ingyō) and is considered an associated satellite mound. However, it was excluded from the Imperial Household Agency's Historic Site, and its mound has been lost.

In approximately 1877, Saisho Atsushi, the governor of [[Sakai Prefecture]], excavated the southern stone coffin, finding bronze burial goods and an iron sword inside, as well as armor buried in the surrounding soil. In 1946, the Osaka Prefecture Board of Education and Kyoto University Archaeology Laboratory investigated another coffin on the northern side, recovering remaining burial goods.

== Stone Coffins and burial goods ==
The northern coffin is an ancient type of house-shaped stone coffin with large circular protrusions on both ends of the lid and body. It was housed within a {{ill|pit-style stone chamber|ja|竪穴式石室|1=Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=竪穴式石室|4=zh|5=豎穴式石室|1=Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|12=draft}} made of piled river stones, measuring 3.4 meters in length and 1 meter in width. burial goods unearthed outside the coffin include a {{ill|horned helmet|ja|衝角付冑|1=Horned Kabuto|lt=Horned helmet|12=draft}}, a set of {{ill|Lamellar armour|ja|挂甲|12=draft}} with components like shoulder, knee, and shin guards, a saddle, {{ill|stirrups|ja|鐙|12=draft}}, bits, leaf-shaped pendants, swords, spears, arrowheads, and farming tools like hoes. Southern burial goods included plate armor (short armor) and other items.

Despite being looted, fragments of belt fittings, small glass beads, and pieces of Sue pottery pottery were found inside and outside the coffin. The Lamellar armour is notable for being exceptionally well-preserved, and the iron-core, wood-plated stirrups and gold-plated saddle fittings are particularly significant. The southern coffin, which lacks protrusions on the body, represents a more modern design. Whether it was also housed in a stone chamber remains unclear. Cylindrical {{ill|haniwa|ja|円筒埴輪|1=Cylindrical Haniwa|12=draft}} surrounded the mound. 

The two stone coffins are currently preserved at {{ill|Dōmyōji Elementary School|ja|藤井寺市立道明寺小学校|12=draft}} in Fujidera City.

<gallery>
File:Nagamochiyama-kofun sekikan.jpg|Stone coffin
File:長持山古墳出土 刳抜式家形石棺.JPG|Replica of the stone coffin. Exhibited at the {{ill|Osaka Prefectural Chikatsu-Asuka Museum|ja|大阪府立近つ飛鳥博物館|12=draft}}.
</gallery>

== Historic Site ==
=== Osaka Prefecture-Designated Historic Site ===
* Tangible designation1
** Two stone coffins from Nagamochiyama Kofun (archaeological materials) - Located at Dōmyōji Elementary School. Designated on March 29, 1974.<ref>[http://www.city.fujiidera.lg.jp/rekishikanko/shiteibunkazai/1387687920890.html Designated Historic Site (Osaka Prefecture and Fujidera City)] (Fujidera City website).</ref>

